post_text:
We are so proud of our students and staff for a very successful first week of school, for both our in-person and remote learners. Students and teachers are beginning to build a strong, positive student-teacher bond, which is so important!

For in-person learning families, we kindly ask families to complete the necessary Daily Health Screening in OnCourse prior to your child entering the school building. It's a very quick online form required for all in-person learners, which will ensure we are following mandated health guidelines.

For remote learning families, please don't hesitate to contact your child's teacher at any time, with questions regarding technology, assignments, etc. We will do our best to respond to all questions and help with any technology issues as quickly as possible.

Have a wonderful Labor Day weekend and we will "see" everyone on Tuesday!

post_text:
As promised, here is a followup to our community zoom meeting on Tuesday, July 21st relating to mask wearing. We are being asked to make heart wrenching decisions about the physical, emotional and social health of our children. There is no one size fits all answer for returning to school. However, we will try our best to communicate the facts and hopefully ease our families back into a safe, productive school routine.

Please take a minute to read this article about mask use. I know some of you had questions regarding the psychological impact of masks on our children...the most important take away from this article states "how you respond to mask wearing can also affect how your child reacts to it."

As always, reach out to one of us with questions, concerns or if you just need a sounding board! Say 'hi' to your kiddos for us too - we miss them!

~Deb, Erin, Jenn

We are entering the homestretch of the school year, and Memorial Day weekend marks the unofficial start of summer for many. We hope our students and families are able to enjoy the long weekend and spend some time honoring those that have died fighting for our country. We know some of our traditions may not be able to take place as we would have hoped, but maybe new traditions will be started this weekend. We would love to see pictures of how you decide to spend this American Remembrance weekend!

post_text: Dear WTSD Families: We know that during this very challenging time many of us, including our students, are having trouble coping with this sudden shift in our everyday lives. We want you to know that there is a very valuable mental health resource available to all children ages 5-21 in the state of New Jersey called the Children's System of Care (CSOC). Many times, services available through CSOC are free to families and available regardless of insurance. CSOC can be accessed by calling 877-652-7624, 24 hours a day. See below for more details.

United Way of Northern New Jersey announces the opening of the ALICE Recovery Fund offering Emergency Financial Assistance for low- and moderate-income workers (Asset Limited Income Constrained Employed) in northern New Jersey who have experienced a loss of income as a direct result of the COVID-19 pandemic.

For more information about the ALICE Recovery Fund visit UnitedWayNNJ.org/ALICErecovery or call 973.993.1160, x700.

The Fund is strictly limited to assisting residents of Hunterdon, Morris, Somerset, Suburban Essex, Sussex and Warren counties. Single adults must have had an annual income below $35,560 without dependents or no more than $88,128 with two or more dependents. Two adult households must have had an annual income below $52,444 without dependents or no more than $103,836 with two or more dependents.

To apply: go to http://www.UnitedWayNNJ.org/ALICEassistance

post_text: Ms. Freitas's 2nd Grade Class have been celebrating Earth Day this week! After talking about reducing, reusing, and recycling, students took part in a STEM challenge to use recyclable materials from around their homes to make amazing new creations! They created bird feeders, magazine/book holders, pencil storage containers, and even a lantern! The class also listened to a read aloud of the Dr. Seuss book, The Lorax, and discussed ways that they can protect the Earth for years to come!

I came across this article from a couple of years ago that addresses anxiety in our children. Especially now that we are all under stress, our own feelings of anxiety may become more and more difficult to tuck away. Anxiety rears its head in many different forms and our youngest are certainly dealing with an environment now where they have little control.

https://gozen.com/8-ways-a-childs-anxiety-shows-up-as-something-else/

Please reach out to Guidance or Child Study Team members anytime... we are here to support your children, but also to help you navigate these challenging times.

Deb, Erin, Jenn

I hope this first day of April finds you and yours safe and slowly settling in to a routine. There will be good days when we can just take a deep breath and be thankful the seats at our dinner table are full and we're not eating out of the car running to activities...other days there might just be too much 'togetherness' as we quietly mourn our old routines... Just know that we will persevere and this too shall pass.

Each month I share a 'Character Calendar' which focuses on a specific character trait. Classroom teachers use the thought for the day to spark conversation or reflection. I've shared April's here with you - please share with your child(ren) as well!

Deb, Erin, and Jenn

post_text:
From Counselor De Jesus, creator of Free to Be Mindful:

As we work through the feelings of anger and depression and move towards acceptance, you may want to ask yourself, "What will I do with this time?" During tough times, we can choose to sulk OR we can choose to recognize the situation, label it for what it is, and do something with it. ⠀
⠀
During the upcoming weeks, will you shuffle through the motions or will you conquer this time? Will you let this time define you or will you define it?⠀
⠀
This week, may we think of how we are going to "level up" and conquer this time of quarantine. ⠀
⠀
How will YOU level up?

As a reminder, please reach out to Deb Tierney, Jenn Borusovic, or Erin Karl if you need support during this time.

Week 2 of remote learning is complete!

post_text: Miss DeFeo's 3rd grade class has been gearing up for the holidays by participating in the 12 Days of Kindness countdown. Each day students reveal a new task to spread kindness throughout the Port Colden community. Some of our tasks so far have been writing thank you notes to staff and kind notes to their math teachers, remembering to hold doors open and say please and thank you, and telling others that they are happy to see them. Since the first day of our countdown, Miss DeFeo's class has noticed how our kind acts inspire others to be kind.

post_text: Last week 6th Grade students in Mr. Graham's Social Studies class completed an Ancient Indian Caste System activity. Students were assigned a caste/class within the Ancient Indian Social Pyramid. Their assigned tasks were determined based on their randomly assigned caste. Students milked cows, fetched water, learned Sanskrit (Ancient writing) and made clothes.
